        <name>7.4.2.4 Inverse of a 2 x 2 matrix</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Find the inverses of the following matrices&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(A={@A@}\), \(B={@B@}\), \(C={@C@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(A^{-1}=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(B^{-1}=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(C^{-1}=\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Recall that the inverse of a \(2 \times 2\) matrix
    \(A = {@matrixabcd@}\) is given by the formula&lt;/p&gt;
\[A^{-1} = \frac{1}{ad - bc} {@matrixdbca@}.\]
&lt;p&gt;We apply this to each of the given matrices.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;For \(A = {@A@}\), we have&lt;/p&gt;
        \[A^{-1} = \frac{1}{{@determinant(A)@}} {@preInv(A)@} = {@ta1@}.\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;For \(B = {@B@}\), we have&lt;/p&gt;
        \[B^{-1} = \frac{1}{{@determinant(B)@}} {@preInv(B)@} = {@ta2@}.\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;For \(C = {@C@}\), we have&lt;/p&gt;
        \[C^{-1} = \frac{1}{{@determinant(C)@}} {@preInv(C)@} = {@ta3@}.\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
